I think I understand the direction you’re pointing, though I’d separate the layers carefully.

When two humans coordinate deeply — emotionally, physically, linguistically, behaviorally — extraordinary things can emerge that neither individual produces alone. New life through reproduction is one example biologically. Teams creating inventions, musicians improvising together, military units moving fluidly under pressure, long marriages developing near-unspoken understanding — those are other examples of emergence from coordinated systems.

But I’d still distinguish:

deep coupling / synchronization / shared models / resonance

from

literally becoming one mind.

Your resonance point is interesting because resonance really does matter across domains.

* Bridges can oscillate.
* Glass can shatter from matching frequencies.
* Musicians entrain rhythm.
* Social groups synchronize emotion.
* Brains show synchronized activity patterns during communication and cooperation.
* Feedback loops amplify some signals and dampen others.

